For your specific four attributes, identify and discuss (giving reason based on graphical and statistical data from Q1 or additional) any missing data or outliers (if any) for each of your four attributes. Document what you plan to do with the missing values and/or outliers

Function for attribute examination¶

In [13]:
def plotAttribute(featureName):
    oneSTD = data[featureName].std()
    twoSTD = oneSTD * 2
    threeSTD = oneSTD * 3
    meanValue = data[featureName].mean()
    print("Attribute:", featureName.upper())
    print("Summary:")
    instances = data.shape[0]
    outsideTwo = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - twoSTD)).sum() + (data[featureName] > (meanValue + twoSTD)).sum())
    outsideThree = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - threeSTD)).sum() +(data[featureName] > (meanValue + threeSTD)).sum())

    print("N outside of two STD:\t", outsideTwo, "\t(", round((outsideTwo/instances) *100, 2),"%)")
    print("N outside of three STD:\t", outsideThree, "\t(", round((outsideThree/instances) * 100, 2),"%)")


    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - oneSTD), label='One STD', c="g")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + oneSTD), c="g")

    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - twoSTD), label='Two STD', c="y")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + twoSTD), c="y")
    
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - threeSTD), label='Three STD', c="r")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + threeSTD), c="r")
    
    data[featureName].hist(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Question 3¶

Mark and clean the data your choices must be based on your documented answer to question 2. Create a CSV file of this clean data called: yourXnumberQ3.csv

For thal, exang and fbs, we're looking for -29 as it is the ONLY invalid value that is present in those attributes.

For trestbps, we're looking for negative values.

In [22]:
# Thal
dataog[["thal"]] = dataog[["thal"]].mask(dataog[["thal"]] == -29, np.NaN)
print("\nNaN Using == -29: ", float(dataog[["thal"]].isnull().sum()))

# Exang
dataog[["exang"]] = dataog[["exang"]].mask(dataog[["exang"]] == -29, np.NaN)
print("\nNaN Using == -29: ", float(dataog[["exang"]].isnull().sum()))

# Fbs
dataog[["fbs"]] = dataog[["fbs"]].mask(dataog[["fbs"]] == -29, np.NaN)
print("\nNaN Using == -29: ", float(dataog[["fbs"]].isnull().sum()))

# Trestbps
dataog[["trestbps"]] = dataog[["trestbps"]].mask(dataog[["trestbps"]] < 0, np.NaN)
print("\nNaN Using < 0: ", float(dataog[["trestbps"]].isnull().sum()))

For exang and trestbps, we are going to remove the rows that have invalid data. They only have very small amount of outliers, both hovering around 1% respectively, so it won't affect the dataset too much.

In [23]:
 # print shape first
print(dataog.shape)

print(dataog.shape)

(552, 14)
(545, 14)

For the rest, we are going to impute the values. Why? Well, there is much greater amounts of data. If we were to delete 345 rows of data, of which the data now has 545, that'd be a serious amount of damage done to the dataset. The overall quality would be much higher, but I am not sure if it would be suitable for a machine learning model. I am also worried about skewing the data.

In [24]:
print(dataog['thal'].mode())
print(dataog['fbs'].mode())

0    3.0
dtype: float64
0    0.0
dtype: float64

As we can see from here, the most common value for thal is 3. For fbs, it is 0. We will impute the missing values with these. However, I have my doubts whether this is the right solution. I am not sure if there is a right solution here, but for the purposes of this CA, this is what I'll do.

I will be giving 345 people more the same '3' value for the thal column, while it is clear from the graphs that people do seem to have the '3' value the most, the data is going to be heavily skewed.

But it means the rest of their data is usable. But one has to question whether it'd be better to remove it entirely or not.

Out of the four variables: Thal (Thalium stress test result, I had to Google this as it was not explained.) and exang induced angina have a low correlation of 0.29. I can only speculate as to why these share a minor correlation. They're both related to the flow of the heart, so I can only hypothesise (Damn it Jim, I'm a programmer, not a doctor!) that if you have angina you will probably have an angina defect as well.

Out of the whole dataset: Num and cp (Heart disease status and chest pain) have a medium correlation of 0.50. Why? I can only hypothesise that the worse your heart disease is, the more likely you are to have chest pain. Also, num and exang share a correlation 0.48, which is medium. Which I can only assume the worse your heart disease is, the more likely you are to suffer with angina!

# Convert to array
array = dataog.values
# get seperated input and classifies, using a deep copy of a list
X = array[:,0:13]
Y = array[:,13]
scaler = preprocessing.Normalizer().fit(X)
normalizedX = scaler.transform(X)
#Convert back to Pandas
normX = pd.DataFrame(normalizedX)
Y = pd.DataFrame(Y)
# Concatinating the dataframes back together
outData = pd.concat([normX, Y], axis=1, sort=False)
# Saving the data
outData.to_csv("x00144631Q5.csv",header=False, index=False)
